# Architecture and Code Quality Rules

## Core Principle

All code must prioritize:
- maintainability
- readability
- reusability
- predictability
- separation of concerns

Code should be easy to understand, easy to change, and hard to break.

---

## 1. No Business Logic in UI Layers

The following layers must NOT contain business logic:
- pages
- screens
- route components
- layout components
- presentational components

UI layers are only responsible for:
- rendering UI
- handling user interaction events
- collecting input values
- passing data to services/hooks/controllers
- displaying response state

UI layers must NOT:
- contain API orchestration logic
- transform domain data in complex ways
- include validation rules beyond simple UI validation
- contain conditional branching for business policy
- directly manage business workflows
- duplicate business rules already defined elsewhere

### Allowed in UI
- local UI state
- modal open/close
- tab switching
- form input binding
- loading/error rendering
- invoking hooks, controllers, or services

### Not allowed in UI
- payment rule calculation
- permission decision logic
- domain-specific validation chains
- multi-step API execution flows
- reusable data transformation logic
- business-dependent filtering or mapping logic

### Bad Example
```ts
if (user.role === "admin" && order.status === "PAID" && order.items.length > 0) {
  await api.refund(order.id)
}